1
00:00:05,808 --> 00:00:09,028
Devotees, they like someone

2
00:00:09,028 --> 00:00:13,988
for who, they realize, 
they aspire to be.

3
00:00:13,988 --> 00:00:16,772
They’re looking to 
the svarūp. 
 

4
00:00:16,772 --> 00:00:23,247
Looking beyond
any perceivable defect.

5
00:00:23,247 --> 00:00:25,059
This is very different. 
 

6
00:00:25,059 --> 00:00:28,709
[Photoshop The Objective Self]

7
00:00:29,017 --> 00:00:32,170
Someone might be a little arrogant,
greedy, this, that …

8
00:00:32,170 --> 00:00:35,295
They’re looking beyond that 
and seeing

9
00:00:35,295 --> 00:00:39,021
if there’s some
devotional substance there. 
 

10
00:00:39,559 --> 00:00:42,446
Guru Mahārāj mentioned, 
there were two devotees in Gauḍīya Math,

11
00:00:42,553 --> 00:00:45,524
they didn’t like each other.
 

12
00:00:46,248 --> 00:00:48,942
And Saraswatī Ṭhākur
was aware of this,

13
00:00:48,942 --> 00:00:51,922
so in a public meeting
he asked each one,
 

14
00:00:51,922 --> 00:00:55,127
“You glorify that person
and that person glorify him.”

15
00:00:55,127 --> 00:00:59,408
He made them praise each other
in open assembly.

16
00:00:59,684 --> 00:01:10,424
So, the one person was looking
and said, “Oh, well …”

17
00:01:10,470 --> 00:01:12,599
And Guru Mahārāj said,

18
00:01:12,630 --> 00:01:15,947
“Нe had to look to the svarūp

19
00:01:15,947 --> 00:01:19,150
to say something good.”
 

20
00:01:22,043 --> 00:01:26,679
But that’s a good thing.

21
00:01:26,679 --> 00:01:36,333
So we’re looking to 
the subjective self,

22
00:01:36,333 --> 00:01:38,401
not the objective self.

23
00:01:38,401 --> 00:01:46,094
We’re willing to photoshop
the objective self,

24
00:01:46,094 --> 00:01:48,889
just look towards
the subjective self

25
00:01:48,889 --> 00:01:50,634
and make adjustments there. 
 

